{
  "texts": [
    "As detailed below, the CNN amplified the classification bias observed in the human participants (see Methods for further details of the model).",
    "First, to test the accuracy of the model, we trained it on the 5,000 arrays that were presented to the participants in level 1 (5,000 arrays = 50 participants × 100 arrays), with class labels based on the objective ranking scores of the arrays (that is, not the human labels).",
    "The model was then evaluated on a 300 out-of-sample test set and showed a classification accuracy of 96%, suggesting that it was highly accurate and did not show a bias if trained on non-biased data (see Table 1).",
    "Next, we trained the model on class labels defined based on the human classification (5,000 samples of arrays; Fig. 1a) and evaluated it on 300 arrays in an out-of-sample test set.",
    "The model classified the average emotion as more sad in 65.33% of the cases, despite only 50% of the arrays being more sad."
  ]
}